 usually denounce Hezbollah as a dangerous terrorist organization and refuse to engage with it, yet even its adversaries need to contend with its durability and resilient popular support. Augustus Richard Norton’s incisive account stands as the most lucid, informed, and balanced analysis of Hezbollah yet written--and this fully revised and updated edition features a new prologue and conclusion, as well as two new chapters largely devoted to the group’s recent activities, including its involvement in Syria. Hezbollah is a work of perennial importance and remains essential reading for anyone who wants to understand the Middle East.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aGeopoliticszMiddle East. 0aIslam and politicszLebanon. 0aShiiteszLebanonxPolitics and government. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / General.2bisacsh  a2003 invasion of Iraq.  a2006 Lebanon War.  aAbbas al-Musawi.  aActivism.  aAl-Jazeera (Jordan).  aAl-Manar.  aAl-Qaeda.  aAli Khamenei.  aAli Shariati.  aAli al-Sistani.  aAmal Movement.  aArab Spring.  aAssassination.  aBaalbek.  aBahrain.  aBashar al-Assad.  aBeirut.  aBeqaa Valley.  aCaliphate.  aCar bomb.  aDruze.  aElectoral district.  aFatah.  aFatwa.  aFouad Siniora.  aFree Syrian Army.  aHafez al-Assad.  aHamas.  aHassan Nasrallah.  aHegemony.  aHosni Mubarak.  aHouthis.  aHusayn ibn Ali.  aIdeology.  aImad Mughniyah.  aIranian Revolution.  aIslam.  aIslamic republic.  aIslamism.  aIsrael Defense Forces.  aIsrael.  aIsraeli-occupied territories.  aIsraelis.  aJews.  aJihad al-Bina.  aJihadism.  aJournal of Palestine Studies.  aJournal of Peace Research.  aKarbala.  aKurds.  aKuwait.  aLebanese Armed Forces.  aLebanese Civil War.  aLebanese National Movement.  aMichel Aoun.  aMichel Suleiman. 